And legacy news media companies are apparently all to happy to help them in this fight.
Section 230 prevents digital companies from being automatically treated as the speaker of any third-party speech they assist in putting online.
Section 230 has never prevented the Justice Department from enforcing federal criminal statutes against online violators, as many have misleadingly argued.
And either way, the spoils will go to the big tech companies that are best able to lobby, contribute, curry favor, or otherwise game the system.
"The easiest lever to hurt tech companies that a lot of people see is 230," Stanford Law School professor Daphne Keller told the Times.